[start section id="20112"]

Reviewed outside colonoscopy, pathology, and radiology reports.
#1 Rectosigmoid cancer
Mr. Quinn presents for evaluation and treatment of rectosigmoid cancer, described 12 to 15-cm above the anal verge on outside exam.  I discussed the development, staging, and treatment of rectosigmoid cancer with the patient and his family members, including the need to discern whether this is truly rectal or more sigmoid, as this would affect rationale for neoadjuvant chemoradiation consideration if T3 or N1 disease is noted, versus consideration of adjuvant chemotherapy as this is more sigmoid and involves lymph nodes.  I have requested tattoo of the distal margin, and he is agreeable to proceeding with immunohistochemistry staining to assess for Lynch syndrome.  Also, one could consider polyposis given his father's history, and therefore we will obtain an extended EGD with sideviewer at the time of his colonoscopy.  Certainly, if duodenal polyps or even cystic fundic gland polyps are identified on EGD, this would be more suggestive of a polyposis syndrome.
I also discussed the role for a colonic stent with the patient, but given the need for therapy in the near future, we at this time will not proceed with that.  Instead, we will make diet recommendations to avoid bulk and utilize a stool softener.
#2 Preoperative medical evaluation
Lab work, chest x-ray, and ECG are pending.  Once these are obtained and satisfactory, the patient is okay for anesthesia.
Discussed with Dr. Lawrence Ashworth, note to follow.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

