[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Quinn is a 46-year-old gentleman who presents to Parkway Regional Center for evaluation and treatment of rectal cancer.  Mr. Quinn developed rectal bleeding and underwent his first colonoscopy April 15, 2010.  A small polyp was removed from the sigmoid at 70 cm (tubular adenoma, low-grade dysplasia) and a partially obstructing mass was noted in the rectosigmoid extending from 12 to 15-cm above the anal verge.  Biopsies demonstrated invasive grade 3 of 4 adenocarcinoma, and SMHWC Pathology confirms the diagnosis.  CT abdomen and pelvis of April 15, 2010, was negative for metastatic disease.  A-1.5-cm cyst was noted in the liver, and a 2-mm right pulmonary nodule was noted.  CEA was 2.  Mr. Quinn is symptomatic with persistent bright-red blood per rectum, increased fragmentation of stools, and also has had fevers and chills periodically for several weeks.  He has lost 20 pounds over the past couple of months.  Prior to the onset of GI symptoms, his baseline bowel pattern was two-to-three stools per day with no incontinence or urgency.
Comorbidities include nicotine dependence (chews tobacco) and hyperlipidemia.  He had cardiac ablation for Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome.  He currently is without any cardiopulmonary complaints.

